e. Compare   Fye   3 and   Paye   5."],"variants":[{"name":"Faille","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Agathe, Andre.","Altered form of French   Faye  . Compare   Fayette   1 and   Foy   5.","French: metonymic occupational name for a torchbearer, from Old French <i>faille</i> ‘torch’ (from Late Latin <i>facilla</i>)."]},{"name":"Fay","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, John Patrick, Donovan, Fergus, Kieran, Liam, Nuala.","English: nickname for a person believed to have supernatural qualities, from Middle English, Old French <i>faie</i> ‘fairy, witch’ (from Late Latin <i>fata</i> ‘fate, destiny’).","English: nickname for a trustworthy person, from Middle English, Old French <i>fei</i> ‘loyalty, trust’."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud De Faye was born in 1193, in Leicester, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom. S